I've noticed that sprites don't appear when using layer depth and a magnified view. For example, the following code will result in no sprite appearing:

``` c#
_spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.BackToFront, transformMatrix: Matrix.CreateScale(2f));
_spriteBatch.Draw(_texture, Vector2.Zero, layerDepth: 1f);
_spriteBatch.End();
```

However, if I change the layer depth to 0.5 or lower, then the above example will work. Specifically, the threshold for the layer depth before the sprite disappears seems to be 1 / scale.

Also note that it doesn't matter what the SpriteSortMode is set to. It still happens regardless of this value.

I've tested this on both the latest Windows DirectX and OpenGL builds with the same results.

One thing I've noticed is that in SpriteBatchItem the Z position is currently being set to the layer depth value. Forcing the Z position to 0 gets things working again, but this is obviously not the correct fix.

Sorry for bad english, I use Google translator.
I'm trying to write a simple shaders just to have a simple look on shader technology.
I had some medium logic pixel shader and it was working wrong. I twice checked it and decided that is bug in monogame. Bug in setting textures to sampler states.
This bugs are already described in monogame issues. You wrote that you are fixed them, but some people still have them occuring.
I tried to reduce my pixel shader code to somehow help identify this bug.
For example:

```
texture Texture;
sampler SecondSampler = sampler_state
{
    Texture = (Texture);
};

sampler TextureSampler : register(s0);

float4 main(float4 position : SV_POSITION0, float4 color : COLOR0, float2 texCoord : TEXCOORD0) : COLOR0
{
    return tex2D(SecondSampler, texCoord) * 0.5f + tex2D(TextureSampler, texCoord) * 0.5f;
}

technique ShaderTechnique
{
    pass DefaultPass
    {
        PixelShader = compile ps_4_0_level_9_1 main();
    }
}
```

So I doing this

``` C#
effect.Parameters["Texture"].SetValue(secondTexture);
spriteBatch.Begin(SpriteSortMode.BackToFront, BlendState.AlphaBlend, SamplerState.PointWrap, null, null, effect);
            {
                spriteBatch.Draw(firstTexture, position, Color.White);
            }
spriteBatch.End();
```

As I expect, this should draw both textures half-transparent on same place, both textures must be visible. But only firstTexture are visible half-transparent, secondTexture is not drawn at all.
Buti if I write in shader not this

```
return tex2D(SecondSampler, texCoord) * 0.5f + tex2D(TextureSampler, texCoord) * 0.5f;
```

but this

```
return tex2D(TextureSampler, texCoord) * 0.5f +  tex2D(SecondSampler, texCoord) * 0.5f;
```

then it works as I expected.
Maybe I don't understand something, and (a+b) != (b+a) for float4 types, but I hope this can be helpful for fixing bug.

I have encountered several problems compiling DirectX Effects. I assume that they are caused by the new preprocessor (https://github.com/mono/MonoGame/issues/1972). Before everything worked fine.

Here are two effects for reproducing the problems:

Effect.fx

```
float4 VS(float4 pos : SV_Position) : SV_Position
{
  return pos;
}

float4 PS() : COLOR
{
  return float4(0, 0, 0, 0);
}

technique
{
  pass
  {
    VertexShader = compile vs_4_0 VS();
    PixelShader = compile ps_4_0 PS();
  }
}
```

Effect2.fx

```
#define DEF0 0
#define DEF1 0
#define DEF2 0
#include "Effect.fx"
```

Effect.fx compiles without a problem. But the following problems appear when compiling Effect2.fx:

**Problem 1:** When Effect.fx does not end with a newline (CRLF) the following error is output:
`Effect.fx(18,2): error X3000: syntax error: unexpected token '#'` 

**Problem 2:** When Effect.fx ends with a newline (CRLF) the following error is output:
`Effect.fx(19,7): error X1500: syntax error : unexpected token '-'`

When I remove one of the #define in Effect2.fx or when I change one of the lines from `#define DEF0 0` to `#define DEF0 1`, it compiles without a problem. Note that these #define don't do anything. So this seems to be a problem purely of the preprocessor.

**Problem 3:** When compiling complex effects with many include files, the line numbers at which errrors are reported are off.

Greetings,

A few points:
- I'm using MonoGame 3.4
- My keyboard layout is AZERTY
- I have checked my language and keyboard settings on my computer and everything is correct

The problem I'm having is that the OpenGL versions of MonoGame seems to ignore the keyboard layout.

I created a little piece of testing code which is:

``` C#
/// <summary>
/// This is called when the game should draw itself.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="gameTime">Provides a snapshot of timing values.</param>
protected override void Draw(GameTime gameTime)
{
    // Testing fields
    Color clearColor = Color.MonoGameOrange;
    KeyboardState keyboardState = Keyboard.GetState();

    if (keyboardState.IsKeyDown(Keys.Escape))
        Exit();

    // Testing code
    if (keyboardState.IsKeyDown(Keys.A))
        clearColor = Color.Black;
    else if (keyboardState.IsKeyDown(Keys.Q))
        clearColor = Color.White;

    // Show the clearColor
    GraphicsDevice.Clear(clearColor);

    base.Draw(gameTime);
}
```

When I'm pressing the A key the screen turns white and when I'm pressing the Q key the screen turns black. It should be inversed. 
When debugging I saw that MonoGame thinks I have a QWERTY keyboard when in fact I have an AZERTY keyboard. But the GameWindow.TextInput event does not suffer from this error. It gives the correct characters.
When testing this piece of code on the WindowsDX version everything worked just as it should, no problems.

Thankyou for the work you guys are doing.
